05728nam a22008535i 9781463241100DE-B159720220110023848.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220110t20212020nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2020058579  a97814632411007 a10.31826/97814632411002doi  a(DE-B1597)583239  a(OCoLC)1248759067  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aBS2325b.B57 2019 4aBS2325b.B57 2019 7aREL0061002bisacsh04a225.4/04622300aAt One Remove: The Text of the New Testament in Early Translations and Quotations :bPapers from the Eleventh Birmingham Colloquium on the Textual Criticism of the New Testament /ced. by Peter Montoro, H.A.G. Houghton. 1aPiscataway, NJ : bGorgias Press, c[2021] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (361 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTexts and Studies (Third Series) ;v240 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIndirect evidence, in the form of early translations (‘versions’) and biblical "ations in ancient writers (‘patristic citations’), offers important testimony to the history and transmission of the New Testament. In addition to their value as early evidence for the Greek New Testament, versions have a textual tradition of their own which is often of considerable historical, theological and ecclesial significance. Early "ations have the potential to provide a form of text which can be attributed to a specific time and location, as well as shedding light on its interpretation. This volume brings together a series of original contributions on these topics, which were the focus of the Eleventh Birmingham Colloquium on the Textual Criticism of the New Testament. It includes an account of the newly-discovered third Old Syriac version of the Gospels, followed by studies of the Coptic, Arabic, Latin and Gothic traditions. Two Greek-Latin bilingual manuscripts are examined, Codex Bezae and the St Gall Bilingual Gospels, along with a comparison of verb forms in these languages. Biblical "ations are considered from Tertullian, Ambrose and John Chrysostom, as well as a work attributed to Rufinus the Syrian which has been key to identifying the origin of the Latin Vulgate: the early printed editions of this version are the subject of another chapter. Although at one remove from Greek New Testament manuscripts, the research described in this volume illustrates not just the ongoing importance and variety of indirect material, but also the way in which it may shape the theory and practice of text-critical scholarship and lead to new insights about this vast and rich tradition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 10. Jan 2022) 4aBible. 4aCriticism, Interpretation/New Testament. 4aReligion. 7aRELIGION / Biblical Criticism & Interpretation / New Testament.2bisacsh1 aBaudoin, Anne-Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFalluomini, Carla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFörster, Hans, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaupt, Benjamin D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoughton, H. A. G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoughton, H.A.G., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLopik, Teunis Van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLorenz, Peter E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMills, Ian N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMontoro, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMontoro, Peter, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPersig, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmit